  <!-- FAQs -->
  <section id="faqs" class="py-16 md:py-24 bg-muted/30">
    <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold mb-8 text-center">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        
        <div class="space-y-6">
          <div class="bg-card border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3">What is commercial remediation?</h3>
            <p class="text-muted-foreground">
              Commercial remediation is repair work that addresses structural defects, water damage, fire damage, mould or compliance failures in commercial buildings. It goes beyond routine maintenance to fix underlying problems and restore safety and functionality.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-card border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3">How quickly should remediation start after a leak?</h3>
            <p class="text-muted-foreground">
              Response within 48 hours significantly reduces secondary damage like mould growth and material degradation. Make safe works and containment should begin immediately, with drying equipment deployed within the first 24 hours where possible.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-card border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3">Can remediation be completed while a site is occupied?</h3>
            <p class="text-muted-foreground">
              Many remediation projects can proceed with the building occupied, using containment barriers, staged works or after-hours scheduling. The approach depends on the type of damage, safety requirements and whether hazardous materials are involved.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-card border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3">When is mould testing required?</h3>
            <p class="text-muted-foreground">
              Mould testing is typically recommended when visible mould exceeds one square metre, when there are persistent odours or when occupants report health symptoms. Testing identifies mould species and guides remediation methods and safety protocols.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-card border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3">Who is responsible for remediation in a lease, tenant or landlord?</h3>
            <p class="text-muted-foreground">
              Responsibility depends on the lease terms and the cause of damage. Landlords typically handle structural defects, building envelope failures and issues arising from building systems. Tenants may be responsible for damage caused by their fit out or operations. Review the lease and obtain legal advice where liability is unclear.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-card border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3">What documentation is usually provided at handover?</h3>
            <p class="text-muted-foreground">
              Handover documentation typically includes completion certificates, test results (moisture readings, air quality, electrical safety), material warranties, waste disposal manifests, before and after photos and compliance certificates where building permits were required.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

